explanation:
To decide if this function violates the MISRA guideline that pointers should point to const-qualified types whenever possible you must examine where const is required/removed and whether the underlying APIs require or modify the data: 

- OS_ObjectIdGetBySearch (prototype): The call explicitly casts (void *)sysdata when passing to this function. You need the exact parameter types (especially the type of the search-argument parameter) to know whether the API expects a non-const void * or a const void *. If the API legitimately requires a non-const pointer that is documented to be modified, the cast may be justified; if the API accepts a const pointer then the cast is unnecessary and a MISRA issue may exist.

- OS_TaskIdMatchSystemData_Impl (prototype / callback signature): This is the callback passed to OS_ObjectIdGetBySearch and likely receives the search-argument. Its parameter constness determines whether the search routine treats sysdata as mutable. If the callback is declared to take a non-const pointer, that explains the cast; if it takes a const pointer, the cast is incorrect.

- OS_TaskValidateSystemData_Impl (prototype): The function is called with sysdata and sysdata_size for validation and in the code it is declared/used as taking a const void *. Confirming its prototype verifies that the local function treats sysdata as const (i.e., no mutation) and supports the argument being const-qualified.

- OS_CHECK_POINTER (macro definition): This macro is invoked on task_id. To confirm whether task_id could/should be declared as a pointer-to-const (or must remain non-const because the function writes through it) you need to see whether the macro or surrounding conventions modify task_id. In practice the function assigns *task_id, so task_id must not be pointer-to-const; still include the macro to show any side-effects relevant to pointer constness.

- osal_id_t (typedef): The typedef of osal_id_t is required to determine whether task_id could/should be a pointer-to-const or whether it is an output parameter (and thus must be non-const). The function writes to *task_id, so having the typedef helps confirm intended usage.

- OS_object_token_t (typedef): The token type is passed to OS_ObjectIdFromToken/OS_ObjectIdRelease and used to derive the returned id. Understanding this type can confirm whether any of those calls require mutating sysdata indirectly (unlikely) and helps determine whether token-related APIs have const-related expectations.

Provide these symbol prototypes/definitions to the next analyst so they can determine if the const is being removed unnecessarily (MISRA violation) or if the underlying APIs legitimately require a non-const pointer.
